    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Positive prints made from the Fox Talbot calotype negative. Although calotype paper could be used to make positive prints from calotype negatives, Talbot's earlier silver chloride paper, commonly called "salted paper," was normally used for that purpose. </Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000020881/International Center of Photography Encyclopedia of Photography (1984)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000094782/Chatters and Jacobs, Recovery of Faded Photographs (1970)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Positieve afdrukken die zijn gemaakt van een Fox Talbot-calotypenegatief. Hoewel calotypepapier zou kunnen worden gebruikt om positieve afdrukken te maken van calotypenegatieven, werd voor dat doel normaal gesproken Talbots eerdere zilverchloridepapier gebruikt, dat vaak 'gezouten papier' werd genoemd.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109894/UvA Talen</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Impressões positivas feitas a partir do negativo do calótipo Fox Talbot. Embora o papel calotipado pudesse ser usado para fazer impressões positivas de negativos calotipados, o papel anterior de cloreto de prata de Talbot, comumente chamado de "papel salgado", era normalmente usado para esse propósito.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000316/CVAA-BR</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109633/CVAA-BR Consortium (2020-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
